    "summary": "Vote B: Afterword cross-traditional section, not Preface",
    "content": "**B** — Afterword, cross-traditional connections section. \n\nThis is exactly the kind of scholarly positioning that the Afterword was designed for. The 诗人/Dichter contrast is a genuine philosophical finding that illuminates the author's departure from Heidegger — but it requires the reader to have already encountered the Poetic (诗意) and the Appendix passage in full. Putting it in the Preface would be both a spoiler (revealing the Appendix's culminating gesture) and incomprehensible (the reader hasn't encountered the concept yet). The Afterword's Section B (existentialist positioning) is the natural home: it can discuss the poet/Dichter contrast alongside the Poetic vs. amor fati, revolt, and Gelassenheit comparisons already planned for that section.\n\nThe shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is a genuinely important insight and deserves prominent placement in the Afterword."
  }
